<dl id="n22053b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n22" href="#n22053b">N22 (VI.B.17)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n22all.htm#n22053b"> 53(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> curtle axe</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Soon after came the priest, clad in a short gown, and with a curtle axe hung round his neck; and when he came to where the pitfall had been dug, he fell into it on the wolf, at which he was much alarmed, and the wolf, who was down there first, was as much afraid of the priest as the priest was of it. <small> Robert B. Douglas, trans., <a name="RBDM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#RBDM"><cite title="source">ONE HUNDRED MERRIE AND DELIGHTSOME STORIES</cite></a> (1923) Story 56</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
